'Manhattan skyline, combining an innovative design with vibrant cultural programming. From start to finish, this history emphasizes the contributions, collaborations, and spirited disagreements that made the planning and construction of Brooklyn Bridge Park a model of natural urban development and public-private partnership. The book includes interviews with Brooklyn residents, politicians, activists, urban planners, landscape architects, and other key participants in the fight for the park. The story of Brooklyn Bridge Park also speaks to larger issues confronting all cities, including the development of postindustrial spaces and the ways to balance public and private interests without sacrificing creative vision or sustainable goals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Nov 2018) 0aParkszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory.1 aShirley, David, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016z978311050018908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255940uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/webs17122423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231542944.jpg  a978-3-11-050018-9  CUP eBook Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-066255-9  CUP eBook Package 2016-2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG